betterquesting:10.desc:8: Welcome to ATM 0! The questbook will provide a basic guide through the early game.
It's that time again - punch some trees! You'll need plenty of wood for the next task.
As you may have discovered already, vanilla pickaxes are disabled. You'll need to create some new tools for your early game mining needs.
Your first pickaxe, assembled in the Tool Station. §9Iguana's Tinker Tweaks §fmodifies the harvest level of ores and pickaxes. This pickaxe will let you gather copper ore for the next upgrade.
The first cast upgrade. You'll need to make this in the smeltery. You can swap the head of your pickaxe in the Tool Station.

§9RotaryCraft§f is a tech mod by Reika_Kalseki, featuring a torque/speed power system with a focus on realism.

Some highlights of the mod include 5x+ ore processing, unbreakable tools and armor, and interactions with Reika's other mods - §9ChromatiCraft§f, §9ElectriCraft§f, and §9ReactorCraft§f.

Don't forget to read the RotaryCraft Handbook! It contains a lot of helpful information that isn't covered in these quests.
This pack includes §9Hardcore Darkness§9§f. You might want some torches.
A bit better than copper.
The first alloy pickaxe head. You can make this in the smeltery by adding copper and tin at a ratio of 3:1.
Check out §9Thermal Expansion§f or §9IndustrialCraft 2§f to make Refined Iron.

The smeltery is your first ore-doubling method. You'll need this to make metal tools.

The required amounts will suffice for a 3x3 inside smeltery, but you can build it up to 7x7 inside.
Check out §9Thaumcraft§f and make a Thaumium Pickaxe.
Next up, the Nether!
Ardite and Cobalt can be found in the Nether.
The last pickaxe you'll ever need? Maybe not, but it will do for now.

The Blast Furnace is your entrypoint into §9RotaryCraft§f. It's used to create Coal Coke and HSLA Steel, along with many other recipes.

You'll need to provide external heat for this block. Later on, you'll be able to use the Friction Heater, but for now a block of lava will provide enough heat.

Coal Coke can be made from Coal in the blast furnace. Between 1 and 9 can be crafted at once, depending on how many slots are filled.

You can make HSLA Steel with regular coal, but using coal coke gives a chance to double the output, making it well worth the time.

The entry level material for the mod, you'll go through quite a bit of this.

You'll need a blast furnace heated to 600C, lava will get you there in a temperate biome. 

Besides iron, you'll need sand, coal or coal coke, and gunpowder, placed in the three left slots in that order. The coal coke will be consumed with each operation, while the other two catalysts have a small chance of being consumed. 

Like coal coke, you can craft up to nine at a time if all the slots are filled with iron.
Most §9RotaryCraft§f machines will be crafted in the worktable.

This is your first power source. It requires a heat source and a water supply.

A simple setup would be an Aqueous Accumulator providing water, with a fire underneath on netherrack. This will keep your engine running at a safe temperature. You can also use lava, but it is much hotter than fire, so you will need cooling fins to keep the engine from exploding.

The friction heater converts rotational energy into heat. 

You can connect this to a furnace for free smelting. With one steam engine, it smelts faster than normal fuel, and it can go even faster with more powerful engines.

The grinder will let you process canola into lubricant, which you'll need in quantity if you want to keep your gearboxes from burning up. Oh, and it also does ore processing.

The grinder requires more torque (128nm) than a steam engine produces (32nm), meaning you'll need a 4:1 gearbox in torque mode to power it with one steam engine. If you don't have a stable lubricant supply yet, you can just use a cheap wood gearbox and let it get damaged.
The tool of choice for moving gears. Right-click to rotate machines and gearboxes, shift+right-click to switch modes on gearboxes.

ChromatiCraft is a magic mod by ReikaKalseki, with a power system based on sixteen colors of light (lumens).

If you've been exploring, you may have already seen (or felt) some crystal pylons.

Later on, you'll be able to prevent them from damaging you, but for now you might want to keep a safe distance (most of the time).

This mod has a heavy focus on discovery and exploration, so this questline will just focus on explanations of mechanics.

Be certain to read the info in the lexicon, not just the quest book!

When you look at your lexicon, you'll see two tabs on the left, and three tabs on the right.

The first tab on the left is the info page, where you can find the descriptions for each fragment you unlock.

The second tab on the left is the recipe page, with a corresponding recipe for any craftable fragment.

The first tab on the right is the progression tab, where you can find clues to progress through the mod.

The second tab on the right is the Recovery tab. If you lose your book, you can recover fragments you've learned at the cost of paper and ink.

The last tab on the right is the notes tab, a space for you to write things down.

You'll find these in various dungeons around the world, both ChromatiCraft dungeons and regular vanilla dungeons.

Sneak + right-click on one in your hotbar to open the decoder, and then place the fragment in the top slot.

After decoding, you can sneak + right-click on your lexicon to open the inventory, and store the fragment.

You can also store blank fragments in the lexicon by holding them over the lexicon in your inventory and left-clicking.

Right-click on the lexicon in your inventory to take them back out.

Your first crystal tool, you'll be using this a lot.

This marks the end of the questline (for now), go forth and explore!

If you think you're stuck somewhere, try to find more fragments.

If you've decoded all the fragments you can, try crafting things or check the progression tab for any new clues you might be able to unlock.
Well this is a pretty obvious milestone, but you'll need a few of these eventually.
Thanks to Et Futurum, you can respawn the dragon just like modern versions.
A brief introduction to some of the milestones in RotaryCraft. If these look interesting, check out the quest chapter for more info!
Used to get bedrock dust for crafting the endgame machines and gear.
There might not be a convenient way to store time in the pack, but this should be a fine replacement.
From a single block to a complex multiblock structure, this will accompany you through the whole mod.
For when the enchanting table just doesn't cut it.
A (sort of) preview of a few of the things you can do. Since ChromatiCraft is a discovery based mod, you'll need to unlock the progression for these items before you can see the recipes.
Those cables can get in the way sometimes. What if you didn't need them?
Sure, Thaumcraft is cool, but what if it was BETTER!
Tesseracts aren't very good at rotating, but maybe this can help?
If you're tired of chugging potions, give these a try.
This spawner would be a lot more useful if it was spawning that one mob you needed...
Unbreakable armor with great protection and upgrades.
Unbreakable tools that come with great enchants.
Harvesting and replanting crops or moving mobs, this fan can do it all.
Easy tree farms, you can even enchant them.
Ever wanted your very own jet turbine? This is your chance! But don't stand too close...
If you thought Mekanism's ore processing was good, take a look at this! 5x ore processing is just the start!
Got a lot of armor you need to recycle? Or maybe you just want to make some tungsten carbide?
Those other spawners not making mobs fast enough? If you've got the power this just might be your solution.
No need to move this quarry, it just keeps going!
